{
  "stem": "1721.3",
  "chunk_idx": 12,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 11.1,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 31,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "And I told her that I needed to-- in fact, I think prior to that, when I joined the Navy, I had to have proof of birth.",
      "word_count": 27
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 31,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "I had no proof of citizenship.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 31,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 9,
      "text": "I wasn't a citizen.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "So, she was able to send me my birth certificate, and it had my real father's name on it.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "It didn't register very much then.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "But at the time when I filled out the application, it said, you may change your name if you'd like, because I had recognized that many people had very unpronounceable names.",
      "word_count": 31
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "And I said, hmm.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "And I guess there was a psychological hurt that was still there, and, so, I changed my name to my father's name, which certainly didn't-- I'm sure my mother didn't like.",
      "word_count": 31
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "She would liked for me to have changed by name to her then married name which was Curlander, which was a very nice name, which, in retrospect, I wouldn't have mind having Curlander as opposed to Daniels, because Curlander is more of a Jewish name than Daniels.",
      "word_count": 47
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "So, anyway, I changed my name to Daniels at that time, and I became a citizen of America.",
      "word_count": 18
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "It was a wonderful day for me, a wonderful day.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "Do you remember it?",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 32,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 9,
      "text": "Obviously?",
      "word_count": 1
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "Well, I remember it.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "The federal building in San Diego.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "I remember being with a lot of people.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "I remember standing up there and taking the vow, feeling very good, having a few friends there, and going through, at that time, changing some of my records with the Navy.",
      "word_count": 31
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "They had to change a lot of my records.",
      "word_count": 9
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "You know, they had to-- I had to make sure that my discharge papers also were consistent with my military record.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "They also had two names on it and all that.",
      "word_count": 10
    }
  ],
